1 age work under the direct supervision of a credentialed staff person
2 who is at least 21 years of age.
3 b. All lead teachers in a child care center shall have at least a North
4 Carolina Early Childhood Credential or its equivalent as determined
5 by the Department. Lead teachers shall either (i) be enrolled in the
6 North Carolina Early Childhood Credential coursework or its
7 equivalent as determined by the Department within six months after
8 becoming employed as a lead teacher or within six months after this
9 act becomes law, whichever is later, and shall complete the credential
10 or its equivalent within 18 months after enrollment.enrollment or (ii)
11 have a minimum of five years of documented experience teaching in a
12 licensed child care facility in this State which shall be deemed
13 equivalent to the North Carolina Early Childhood Credential.
14 c. For child care centers licensed to care for 200 or more children, the
15 Department, in collaboration with the North Carolina Institute for
16 Early Childhood Professional Development, shall establish categories
17 to recognize the levels of education achieved by child care center
18 administrators and teachers who perform administrative functions.
19 The Department shall use these categories to establish appropriate
20 staffing based on the size of the center and the individual staff
21 responsibilities.
22 d. Effective January 1, 1998, an operator of a licensed family child care
23 home shall be at least 21 years old and have a high school diploma or
24 its equivalent. Operators of a family child care home licensed prior to
25 January 1, 1998, shall be at least 18 years of age and literate. Literate
26 is defined as understanding licensing requirements and having the
27 ability to communicate with the family and relevant emergency
28 personnel. Any operator of a licensed family child care home shall be
29 the person on-site providing child care.
30 e. The Commission shall adopt standards to establish appropriate
31 qualifications for all staff in child care centers. These standards shall
32 reflect training, experience, education and credentialing and shall be
33 appropriate for the size center and the level of individual staff
34 responsibilities. It is the intent of this provision to guarantee that all
35 children in child care are cared for by qualified people. Pursuant to
36 G.S. 110-106, no requirements may interfere with the teachings or
37 doctrine of any established religious organization. The staff
38 qualification requirements of this subdivision do not apply to
39 religious-sponsored child care facilities pursuant to G.S. 110-106."
