25 CLARIFY RULES ON MULTIUSE CHILD CARE CENTERS
26 SECTION 1.4. The Department of Health and Human Services, Division of Child
27 Development and Early Education (Division), in coordination with the Child Care Commission,
28 shall work to clarify the rules governing multiuse child care centers to ensure each of the
29 following:
30 (1) Allow the use of existing buildings to house multiunit child care centers and
31 include mixed-age centers if they meet the requirements outlined in the rules
32 regarding multiunit child care centers.
33 (2) Grant individual licenses within a multiunit child care center based on the
34 square footage used by each owner.
35 Applicants who meet the pre-licensing guidelines and are awarded a license by the
36 Division shall be considered eligible to qualify as a tenant in a multiuse facility.
37
38 PART II. SCHOOL-AGE FLEXIBILITIES
39 SECTION 2.2.(a) G.S. 110-91 reads as rewritten:
40 "§ 110-91. Mandatory standards for a license.
41 All child care facilities shall comply with all State laws and federal laws and local ordinances
42 that pertain to child health, safety, and welfare. Except as otherwise provided in this Article, the
43 standards in this section shall be complied with by all child care facilities. However, none
44 Notwithstanding any provision of law or rule to the contrary, any building and grounds which
45 are currently approved for school occupancy and which house a public or private elementary or
46 middle school shall be deemed to have met the space and equipment, sanitation, fire, and building
47 code requirements for a licensed child care facility when the building and grounds are serving
48 the same, or a subset of the same, school-age children in an out-of-school child care program.
49 None of the standards in this section apply to the school-age children of the operator of a child
50 care facility but do apply to the preschool-age children of the operator. Children 13 years of age
51 or older may receive child care on a voluntary basis provided all applicable required standards
Senate Bill 528-Third Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 are met. The standards in this section, along with any other applicable State laws and federal laws
2 or local ordinances, shall be the required standards for the issuance of a license by the Secretary
3 under the policies and procedures of the Commission except that the Commission may, in its
4 discretion, adopt less stringent standards for the licensing of facilities which provide care on a
5 temporary, part-time, drop-in, seasonal, after-school or other than a full-time basis.
6 …
7 (6) Space and Equipment Requirements. – There shall be no less than 25 square
8 feet of indoor space for each child for which a child care center is licensed,
9 exclusive of closets, passageways, kitchens, and bathrooms, and this floor
10 space shall provide during rest periods 200 cubic feet of airspace per child for
11 which the center is licensed. There shall be adequate outdoor play area for
12 each child under rules adopted by the Commission which shall be related to
13 the size of center and the availability and location of outside land area. In no
14 event shall the minimum required exceed 75 square feet per child. The outdoor
15 area shall be protected to assure the safety of the children receiving child care
16 by an adequate fence or other protection. A center operated in a public school
17 shall be deemed to have adequate fencing protection. A center operating
18 exclusively during the evening and early morning hours, between 6:00 P.M.
19 and 6:00 A.M., need not meet the outdoor play area requirements mandated
20 by this subdivision.
21 Each child care facility shall provide indoor area equipment and
22 furnishings that are child size, sturdy, safe, and in good repair. Each child care
23 facility that provides outdoor area equipment and furnishings shall provide
24 outdoor area equipment and furnishings that are child size, sturdy, free of
25 hazards that pose a threat of serious injury to children while engaged in normal
26 play activities, and in good repair. The Commission shall adopt standards to
27 establish minimum requirements for equipment appropriate for the size of
28 child care facility. Space shall be available for proper storage of beds, cribs,
29 mats, cots, sleeping garments, and linens as well as designated space for each
30 child's personal belongings.
31 The Division of Child Development of the Department of Health and
32 Human Services shall establish and implement a policy that defines any
33 building which is currently approved for school occupancy and which houses
34 a public or private elementary or middle school to include the playgrounds
35 and athletic fields as part of the school building when that building is used to
36 serve school-age children in after-school out-of-school child care programs.
37 Playgrounds Except as otherwise provided in this section, playgrounds and
38 athletic fields referenced in this section that do not meet licensure standards
39 promulgated by the North Carolina Child Care Commission shall be noted on
40 the program's licensure and rating information.
41 …."
42 SECTION 2.2.(b) The Child Care Commission shall adopt or amend any rules to
43 ensure uniformity and consistency in application of the exemptions for school-age children in
44 out-of-school child care programs as provided in this section.
